04877nam a22007335i 9781503605695DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017038610  a97815036056957 a10.1515/97815036056952doi  a(DE-B1597)563656  a(OCoLC)1178769669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHC427.95b.C433414 2018 4aHC427.95 7aBUS0350002bisacsh04a338.09512231 aChen, Ling, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManipulating Globalization :bThe Influence of Bureaucrats on Business in China /cLing Chen. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Walter H. Shorenstein Asia-Pacific Research Center00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tMajor Abbreviations -- tChapter 1. Bureaucrats, Businesses, and Economic Policies in a Globalized China -- tChapter 2. Chasing Foreign Capital -- tChapter 3. From FDI Attraction to Domestic Competitiveness -- tChapter 4. Local Policy Making, Globalized Coalitions, and Resource Allocation -- tChapter 5. The Microfoundation of State Intervention and Policy Effectiveness -- tChapter 6. Varieties of Local Capitalism in Historical Perspective -- tChapter 7. Making Economic Policies Work -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe era of globalization saw China emerge as the world's manufacturing titan. However, the "made in China" model-with its reliance on cheap labor and thin profits-has begun to wane. Beginning in the 2000s, the Chinese state shifted from attracting foreign investment to promoting the technological competitiveness of domestic firms. This shift caused tensions between winners and losers, leading local bureaucrats to compete for resources in government budget, funding, and tax breaks. While bureaucrats successfully built coalitions to motivate businesses to upgrade in some cities, in others, vested interests within the government deprived businesses of developmental resources and left them in a desperate race to the bottom. In Manipulating Globalization, Ling Chen argues that the roots of coalitional variation lie in the type of foreign firms with which local governments forged alliances. Cities that initially attracted large global firms with a significant share of exports were more likely to experience manipulation from vested interests down the road compared to those that attracted smaller foreign firms. The book develops the argument with in-depth interviews and tests it with quantitative data across hundreds of Chinese cities and thousands of firms. Chen advances a new theory of economic policies in authoritarian regimes and informs debates about the nature of Chinese capitalism. Her findings shed light on state-led development and coalition formation in other emerging economies that comprise the new "globalized" generation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBureaucracyxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aBureaucracy. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aGlobalization. 0aIndustrial policyzChina. 0aIndustrial policy. 0aLocal governmentzChina. 0aLocal government. 4aChina. 4abureaucrats. 4abusinesses. 4acoalitions. 4aeconomic policy. 4aforeign investment. 4aglobalization. 4alocal economy. 4aupgrading. 4avarieties of capitalism (VoC). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503605695zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978